In this article, President Obama discusses his decision to visit Ghana as his first destination in sub-Saharan Africa. He highlights Ghana's successful elections and commitment to democratic governance as reasons for choosing the country. He also emphasizes the importance of good governance in achieving prosperity and highlights the need for better governance in Africa. The President mentions that development assistance should be accompanied by investment and that good governance is necessary to attract investment. He discusses the role of technology in improving aid delivery and mentions the importance of low-tech solutions for agricultural productivity. The President believes that Africans are responsible for the development of Africa and that African leadership should take responsibility and be held accountable. He hopes that by the end of his presidency, the United States will have been an effective partner in building institutions and improving standards of living in Africa.